Anonymous Tue 28 Aug 2018 03:02:13 No.17939164 Report
Quoted By: >>17939412 >>17939428
>>17938897
Plan out your story first. New writers tend to just make shit up as it goes, but that can often lead to writing oneself into a roadblock where they don’t know how to write themselves out of the mess that they’ve started.

Grammar and punctuation are king. English has its own set of rules. If you want to appeal to everyone, then you should follow the proper procedures in syntax and punctuation, greentext and prose be damned because just because you’re writing in a different format doesn’t mean you should abandon what an elementary school child can do.

Force yourself to be descriptive and show instead of telling. Despite being praised as a great storyteller, Strong falls into the trap of skimming over scenes and not putting nearly enough focus into what’s important, weakening the emotional impact of what could be good moments. Don’t be like Strong. Be like Hobo, who can spend up to several thousands of words describing one smut scene, going into the characters’ emotions as well as detailing their actions with clarity.

Learn to write believable interactions. To do that, just go read novels. Go read shit that you never really cared about in high school literature class because they allow your to learn how to write people as well as how people talk to each other.

Don’t be a faggot. If someone hands you valid criticism, take it. Don’t deflect their points by saying shit like “oh that’s just a habit I picked up somewhere” or “I’m just writing it for fun.” You put your work onto public space, don’t expect people to not talk about it.
